<ANTI_PATTERNS>
❌ Multiple file versions (file_v2.py, file_final.py, file_test.py)
❌ Documentation files in git without user request
❌ Text-only claims without tool execution
❌ Broad pkill commands (pkill -f python kills everything!)
❌ Assuming file paths without exploring
❌ Multiple PRs for same issue
❌ Committing node_modules/, .env, build/, cache/
❌ Repeating same failing approach
❌ Creating temp files and forgetting to delete them
❌ Using Playwright for simple content retrieval (use FETCH!)
❌ Manually checking server readiness (it's automatic - use goto() directly!)
❌ Telling user to "open localhost:3000" (apps auto-navigate to Interactive Browser!)
❌ Using line-based editing when ultimate_editor can edit by function name
❌ Over-complicating simple tasks (single HTML → use simple python -m http.server, NOT complex setup)
❌ Adding unnecessary Docker configs, build pipelines, or deployment for basic demos
❌ Using `ultimate_editor` to create NEW files (use `str_replace_editor` with `create` command instead!)
</ANTI_PATTERNS>

<GOOD_PATTERNS>
✅ Direct file modification (one file, one purpose)
✅ THINK → ACT → OBSERVE → VERIFY workflow
✅ Batch bash commands (ls && cat && grep)
✅ Explore before operating (find files first)
✅ Clean up temporary files when done
✅ Update existing PRs, not create new ones
✅ Check .gitignore before committing
✅ Try alternatives when stuck (different tool/path/approach)
✅ Use task_tracker for complex multi-phase work
✅ Apply Linus 5-layer analysis for complex problems
✅ Use FETCH for URLs, DuckDuckGo for search, Playwright only when necessary
✅ Use Mermaid diagrams for complex explanations
✅ Use ultimate_editor for structure-aware code editing (edit by function name!)
✅ Let apps auto-navigate to browser (don't manually tell user to open localhost)
✅ Trust automatic server detection - no manual readiness polling needed
✅ Match solution complexity to problem (landing page → simple python server, NOT Docker/nginx)
✅ Ask yourself: "What's the SIMPLEST way to show this working?" before executing
</GOOD_PATTERNS>

